etropolitan Museum of Art, 1930w(OCoLC)780066752. 0aChildren's bulletin ;vv. 11, no. 4.40uhttps://libmma.contentdm.oclc.org/digital/collection/p15324coll10/id/9376zFull text from Watson Library Digital Collections  a.b2210632704157cam a2200637 i 1285971146OCoLC20231026135905.0m     o  d        cr |||||||||||211122s2013    nyua    obc   000 0 eng d  z9780300197044q(Yale University Press)  z0300197047q(Yale University Press)  z9781588394996q(The Metropolitan Museum of Art)  z1588394999q(The Metropolitan Museum of Art)  aWTUbengerdacWTUdOCLCFdOCLCOdOCLCQ 4aU878b.B74 2013eb04a623.4/41qOCoLC223/eng/202302161 aBreiding, Dirk H.,eauthor.0http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n2005001277.12aA deadly art :bEuropean crossbows, 1250-1850 /cDirk H. Breiding.30aEuropean crossbows, 1250-1850. 1aNew York :bThe Metropolitan Museum of Art,c[2013] 2aNew Haven :bDistributed by Yale University Press. 4c©2013.  a1 online resource (viii, 151 pages) :billustrations (chiefly color)  atextbtxt2rdacontent.  astill imagebsti2rdacontent.  acomputerbc2rdamedia.  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier.  aIncludes bibliographical references (pages 149-151)0 aDirector's foreword / Thomas P. Campbell -- European crossbows: an introduction -- 1. Early crossbows -- 2. Crossbows with steel bows -- 3. Pellet crossbows -- 4. Special types of crossbows -- 5. Spanning devices -- 6. Projectiles and their storage.  a"The advent of the crossbow more than 2,500 years ago effected dramatic changes for hunters and warriors. For centuries, it was among the most powerful and widely used handheld weapons, and its popularity endures to this day. A Deadly Art presents a lively, accessible survey of the crossbow's "golden age," along with detailed descriptions of twenty-four remarkable examples. Beginning in the middle ages, the European aristocracy's enthusiasm for the crossbow heralded shooting competitions and pageants that featured elaborately decorated weapons bearing elegant embellishments of rare materials and prized artistry. In addition to being highly functional, these weapons were magnificent works of art. A Deadly Art includes fascinating descriptions of crossbows used by Margaret of Savoy and Holy Roman Emperors Maximilian I and Charles V, among others."--Publisher's description.  aDescription based on print version.20aMetropolitan Museum of Art (New York, N.Y.).bDepartment of Arms and ArmorvCatalogs.27aMetropolitan Museum of Art (New York, N.Y.).bDepartment of Arms and Armor.2fast0(OCoLC)fst01834533. 0aCrossbowszEuropexHistoryvCatalogs. 0aCrossbowszNew York (State)zNew YorkvCatalogs. 6aArbalètesxHistoirevCatalogueszEurope. 6aArbalètesvCatalogueszNew York (État)zNew York. 7aCrossbows.2fast0(OCoLC)fst00884181. 7aArmbrust.2gnd. 7aEurope.2fast0(OCoLC)fst01245064. 7aNew York (State)zNew York.2fast0(OCoLC)fst01204333. 4aKatalog. 7aCatalogs.2fast0(OCoLC)fst01423692. 7aCollection catalogs.2fast0(OCoLC)fst01986236. 7aHistory.2fast0(OCoLC)fst01411628. 7aCollection catalogs.2lcgft0http://id.loc.gov/authorities/genreForms/gf2017027228. 7aCatalogues de collection.2rvmgf. 0aElectronic books. 0aKatalog.2 aMetropolitan Museum of Art (New York, N.Y.).bDepartment of Arms and Armor,erepository.0http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n98106876.2 aMetropolitan Museum of Art (New York, N.Y.),epublisher.0http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n79129629.08iPrint version:aBreiding, Dirk H.tDeadly art.dNew York : The Metropolitan Museum of Art, [2013]w(OCoLC)866950346.40zFull text from MetPublicationsuhttps://www.metmuseum.org/research/metpublications/A_Deadly_Art_European_Crossbows_1250_1850  a.b2211827504242cam a2200685Ii 856650289OCoLC20231026150830.0m     o  d        cr |n|||||||||130823s1980    nyua    ob    001 0 eng    a80011497  z0691039569 (print)  z9780691039565 (print)  z0870992295 (print)  z97808709